Exercise 0.32

A. Use the ‘Pythagorean theorem of Baseball’ model to predict the winning percentage for the Chicago Cubs, who scored 808 runs and allowed 556 runs in the 2016 season.
808^2/(808^2+556^2) * 100
## [1] 67.86528
B. The Chicago Cubs actually won 103 games and lost 59 in the 2016 season. Determine the winning percentage and also determine the residual from the Pythagorean model (by taking the observed winning percentage minus the predicted winning percentage).
103/(103+59) * 100
## [1] 63.58025
63.58025-67.86528
## [1] -4.28503
C. Interpret what this residual value means for the 2016 Cubs.

The team did worse than expected according to the predictive model by a win percentage of 4.29 points.

D. Repeat parts (a–c) for the 2016 San Diego Padres, who scored 686 runs and allowed 770 runs, while winning 68 games and losing 94 games.
686^2/(686^2+770^2) * 100
## [1] 44.24991
68/(68+94) * 100
## [1] 41.97531
41.97531-44.24991
## [1] -2.2746
E. Which team (Cubs or Padres) fell short of their Pythagorean expectations by more?

The Cubs fell short of their Pythagorean expectations by more.

F. Which team exceeded their Pythagorean expectations the most? Describe how this team’s winning percentage compares to what is predicted by their runs scored and runs allowed.

The Texas Rangers exceeded their Pythagorean expectation most with a residual of 8.12 percentage points: they were predicted to have a win rate of 50.53% and had an actual win rate of 58.64%.

G. Which team fell furthest below their Pythagorean expectations? Describe how this team’s winning percentage compares to what is predicted by their runs scored and runs allowed.

The Tampa Bay Rays fell furthest below their Pythagorean expectation most with a residual of -5.07 percentage points: they were predicted to have a win rate of 47.04% and had an actual win rate of 41.98%.

Exercise 1.20

#install.packages("Stat2Data")
library(Stat2Data)
library(ggplot2)
data("GrinnellHouses")
A. The file GrinnellHouses contains data from 929 house sales in Grinnell, Iowa, between 2005 and into 2015. Make a scatterplot with ListPrice on the horizontal axis and SalePrice on the vertical axis. Comment on the pattern.
ggplot(GrinnellHouses, aes(ListPrice, SalePrice)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

A strong linear trend appears between the two variables where Sale Price increases as List Price increases.

B. Find the least squares regression line for predicting sale price of a home based on list price of that home.
model1 <- lm(SalePrice~ListPrice, GrinnellHouses)
model1
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SalePrice ~ ListPrice, data = GrinnellHouses)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)    ListPrice  
##   -144.8329       0.9431

SalePrice = 0.9431ListPrice - 144.8329

C. Interpret the value (not just the sign) of the slope of the fitted model in the context of this setting.

For every increase of 1000 dollars in the list price, the sale price increases by 943.1 dollars.

Exercise 1.22

A. Refer to the GrinnellHouses datset. What sales price would the fitted model predict for a house that has a $99,500 listing price?
(0.9431*99500) - 144.8329
## [1] 93693.62

$93,693.62

B. The house at 1317 Prince Street has a listing value of $99,500 and a sales price of $95,000. Find the residual for this data point.
95000-93693.62
## [1] 1306.38

$1306.38

C. Does the linear regression model appear to be a good summary of the relationship between list price and sales price for houses in Grinnell, Iowa?
plot(model1, 1:2)

The p-value of <2e-16 indicates that the linear model might present a good summary of the relationship between list prices and sale prices. However, the residual vs fitted plot indicates that the variance of fitted values increases as the numbers get larger, while the Q-Q plot appears to be heavy-tailed, indicating that the residuals are not normally distributed.

data("MathEnrollment")

ggplot(MathEnrollment, aes(AYear, Fall)) + 
  geom_point()

ggplot(MathEnrollment, aes(AYear, Spring)) + 
  geom_point()

In the fall, enrollment in maths decreases over the years, while it increases in the spring.

Exercise 1.44

data("TextPrices")
A. The price and number of pages of a random sample of 30 textbooks from Cal Poly was recorded to investigate the question of whether the number of pages can be used to predict price. Produce the relevant scatterplot to investigate the students’ question. Comment on what the scatterplot reveals about the question.
ggplot(TextPrices, aes(Pages, Price)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The scatterplot indicates that a higher number of pages correlates with a higher price.

B. Determine the equation of the regression line for predicting price from number of pages.
model2 <- lm(Price~Pages, TextPrices)
summary(model2)

C. Produce and examine relevant residual plots, and comment on what they reveal about whether the conditions for inference are met with these data.
plot(model2, 1:2)

The residual vs fitted plot does not appear to display homoscedasticity since the values are more spread out as the fitted values become larger, while the Q-Q plot appears to have a light-tailed distribution. In light of this, the conditions for inference with this data are not met and therefore normality cannot be assumed.
